{"batch":"naming_quality","batch_index":11,"assessments":{"naming_quality":81.0},"dimension_notes":{"naming_quality":{"evidence":["Most helper and domain names are readable (`extract_team_context`, `count_defensive_fouls`, `build_valid_possessions`), but the WMI calculation scripts repeatedly switch to single-letter names like `l`, `f`, `n`, `m`, `n1`, and `n0`, so a reader has to keep the formula comment in mind to know what each value represents (`calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py:9-45`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:133-149`).","The season-processing scripts also rely on terse abbreviations for non-math concepts such as `gid`, `grp`, `comps`, and `max_num`, which makes control flow readable only after tracing nearby code (`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:37-42`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:152-175`, `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:28-40`, `step2_build_possessions.py:34-47`).","There is some vocabulary drift between explicit business names and symbolic column names: one file exposes `foul_called_this_possession` then immediately maps it into `F_t`, `L_t`, `N_t`, `M_t`, while another works only in the symbolic form, so the naming standard is not consistent across related scripts (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:56-69`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:57-73`)."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high"}},"issues":[{"dimension":"naming_quality","identifier":"symbolic_metric_locals_hide_wmi_intent","summary":"Single-letter WMI locals force readers to decode the formula instead of the code","related_files":["calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["`calculate_wmi_rawgame` stores the core series as `l`, `f`, `n`, and `m`, then derives `n1` and `n0`, even though these values mean prior-foul flag, foul flag, next-foul flag, and weighted foul metric (`calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py:9-45`).","`game_wmi_components` and `build_possession_table_for_game` repeat the same symbolic naming style with `f`, `l_vals`, `n_vals`, `m_vals`, and output columns `F_t`, `L_t`, `N_t`, `M_t`, so the same concept is only understandable if the reader already knows the paper notation (`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:133-149`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:57-73`)."],"suggestion":"Rename local variables to intent-bearing names such as `prior_foul_flags`, `current_foul_flags`, `next_foul_flags`, `weighted_foul_values`, `prior_window_count`, and `outside_window_count`; keep the symbolic column names only at the final dataframe boundary if they are required by the metric definition.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"wmi_symbolic_naming"},{"dimension":"naming_quality","identifier":"non_math_abbreviations_reduce_script_readability","summary":"Terse abbreviations like `gid`, `grp`, `sr`, and `max_num` weaken otherwise descriptive scripts","related_files":["calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","step2_build_possessions.py"],"evidence":["The season crawler uses `gid` for game IDs in `fetch_status`, `fetch_game_json_with_retry`, `process_game`, and the futures map; that abbreviation is repeated often enough that it becomes local jargon instead of a one-off short name (`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:37-42`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:83-103`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:152-170`).","`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py` uses `grp`, `sr`, `sh`, and `sa` inside score extraction, even though nearby names are much clearer like `offense_team_id` and `score_difference` (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:28-44`).","Other scripts continue the same pattern with `grp` for grouped possessions, so the abbreviated naming is a subsystem habit rather than a single local exception (`categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:28-31`, `step2_build_possessions.py:34-47`)."],"suggestion":"Expand repeated abbreviations to full domain names such as `game_id`, `possession_group_df`, `score_row`, `score_home`, `score_away`, and `max_game_number` so readers can skim the scripts without translating shorthand.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"wmi_symbolic_naming"},{"dimension":"naming_quality","identifier":"mixed_domain_and_formula_vocab_causes_convention_drift","summary":"Related scripts alternate between descriptive foul names and formula symbols without a stable naming boundary","related_files":["build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py"],"evidence":["`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py` computes `has_def_foul` and stores it as `foul_called_this_possession`, then immediately mirrors it into `F_t`; the same concept gets two naming schemes in one function (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:31-32`, `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:56-69`).","`categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py` uses descriptive names like `called_in_last2` and `called_in_next2` alongside `L_t`, `F_t`, `N_t`, `M_t`, while `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py` skips the descriptive layer and uses only symbolic names in the produced table (`categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:84-100`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:62-73`)."],"suggestion":"Pick one naming boundary for the metric: use descriptive internal names everywhere and translate to `L_t`/`F_t`/`N_t`/`M_t` only in final CSV columns, or adopt a shared helper that makes the symbolic mapping explicit across all scripts.","confidence":"medium","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"wmi_symbolic_naming"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["The code mixes research-paper notation with application code, so symbolic names leak past the data-output boundary into everyday control flow.","These scripts appear to have been written as small standalone analyses, which encourages local shorthand instead of a shared naming convention."],"likely_symptoms":["`gid`, `grp`, `sr`, `sh`, `sa`, `max_num`","`l`, `f`, `n`, `m`, `n1`, `n0`","parallel use of `has_def_foul` and `F_t` for the same concept"],"possible_false_positives":["Short dataframe aliases inside tiny comprehensions were not treated as issues by themselves; the findings focus on repeated abbreviations that shape whole functions."]}}
